demo_features = ['AGE', 'SEX', 'POVERTY', 'EDUC']
health_features = ['BMICALC', 'VEGENO', 'HRSLEEP', 'VIG10DMIN', 'CIGDAYMO', 'ALCDAYSYR']

X_features = demo_features + health_features
y_feature = 'DIABETICEV'

columns = [y_feature] + X_features
In [4]:
data = df[columns].copy()

#DIABETICEV is 1 (No) or 2 (Yes)
data = data[data['DIABETICEV'].isin([1, 2])]
data['DIABETICEV'] = data['DIABETICEV'].replace({1: 0, 2: 1})

#Removed rows with invalid codes (996, 997, 998, 999)
invalid_codes = [996, 997, 998, 999]
for col in X_features:
    data = data[~data[col].isin(invalid_codes)]

data = data[data['AGE'] <= 120]
data = data[data['BMICALC'] < 90]
data = data[data['HRSLEEP'] <= 24]
data = data[data['SEX'].isin([1, 2])]

data.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

print("Data shape after cleaning:", data.shape)
print(data.head())

After SMOTE and hyperparameter tuning, the RBF SVM achieved the highest overall accuracy (~ 82%), outperforming both Linear (~ 69%) and Polynomial (~ 69%) SVMs. However, Linear and Polynomial SVMs demonstrated better recall for identifying diabetic individuals compared to RBF.¶

In [35]:
def plot_roc_curve(model, X, y, name, color, ax):
    y_score = model.decision_function(X)
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y, y_score)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

    ax.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f'{name} (AUC = {roc_auc:.2f})', color=color)
    return ax

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,8))

#Linear SVM ROC
plot_roc_curve(svm_linear_best_balanced, X_test_scaled, y_test, name='Linear SVM', color='blue', ax=ax)

#RBF SVM ROC
plot_roc_curve(svm_rbf_best_balanced, X_test_scaled, y_test, name='RBF SVM', color='green', ax=ax)

#Poly SVM ROC
plot_roc_curve(svm_poly_best_balanced, X_test_scaled, y_test, name='Poly SVM', color='purple', ax=ax)

ax.set_title('ROC Curve Comparison of Tuned SVM Models')
ax.set_xlabel('False Positive Rate')
ax.set_ylabel('True Positive Rate')
ax.legend(loc='lower right')
ax.grid()
plt.show()

ROC curve analysis showed the Linear SVM model achieving the highest AUC (0.80), indicating the strongest overall ability to discriminate between diabetic and non-diabetic individuals.¶
